d popularity firstly through having been borne by an early Christian saint who was a disciple of Saint Paul, and later because it was selected as a symbolic name by a number of early popes. There has also been some confusion with the personal name <i>Clemence</i> (from Latin <i>Clementia</i>, meaning ‘mercy’, an abstract noun derived from the adjective; in part a masculine name from Latin <i>Clementius</i>, a later derivative of <i>Clemens</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, especially Italian   Clemente  , and also their derivatives."],"variants":[{"name":"Clem","meanings":["English (Somerset): from a short form of the personal name   Clement   or of the female form, <i>Clemence</i>.","Americanized form of German <b>Klemm</b> and German or Dutch <b>Klem</b>: from a short form of the personal name   Klemens  ."]},{"name":"Clements","meanings":["English, Irish (Tyrone and Antrim), and Dutch: variant of   Clement  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Clementz   and Slovenian patronymic <b>Klemenc</b> (see   Klements  )."]},{"name":"Clemente","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Elia, Manuel, Cesar, Fernando, Luis, Rafael, Alfredo, Andres, Armando, Gerardo.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Salvatore, Vito, Gino, Angelo, Nicola, Rocco, Enrico, Guido, Marco, Matteo.  Portuguese Joaquim.","Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese: from the personal name<i>Clemente</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Crimi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Gaetano, Vita, Cosimo, Giuseppe, Luciano, Luigi, Sal, Tommaso.","Italian (Sicily): from an altered form of the medieval Greek personal name <i>Klēmēs</i>, from Latin <i>Clemens</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Chimenti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Francesco, Filomena, Guido.","Italian (southern): variant of <b>Clementi</b> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clemon","meanings":["English: probably from a variant of the personal name   Clement  .","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish and northern Irish   McClymont  ."]},{"name":"Klehm","meanings":["North German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Klement</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clementson","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Clement   + <i>-son</i>. See also   Clements   and   Clemson  .","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Klementsson</b> or <b>Clementsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Klement</i>,   Clement  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian <b>Clementsen</b> or <b>Klementsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."]},{"name":"Kelemen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Andras, Gabor, Geza, Imre, Laszlo, Tibor, Bela, Gyula, Istvan, Jozsef, Karoly, Leszlo.","Hungarian, Croatian, Slovak, Rusyn, and Slovenian: from the personal name <i>Kelemen</i>, Hungarian form of   Clement  . The Hungarian surname is also common in Romania."]},{"name":"Climie","meanings":["Scottish: from a Scots pet form of the personal name   Clement  ."]}]},{"name":"Henri","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Henry</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henri I Clement d'Argentan was born about 1170, in Argentan, Orne, Lower Normandy, France, his father, Sieur Robert III Clement d'Argent